english:
  title: Biographical Account of Minister Ki, Duke of Three Realms
  author: Lee Gok
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Minister Ki bore the name Zao, and was also styled Zao. A native of Haengju, he first rose through his family's merit to the rank of Sanwon. In the gengyin year of Zhiyuan, when the rebel Hadan, follower of the traitor Nayan, fled eastward with his forces into Jinpan and invaded our borders, spreading terror wherever they went with slaughter and rapine, Minister Ki served as a Deputy Commander of the Central Army. He carried the great standard and charged forward, earning considerable renown. When the rebels were subdued, he rose through successive promotions to become Inspector of the General Bureau. He was then dispatched as Magistrate of Seonzhou, where his administration was praised for its competence and the people mourned his departure.

    He came from successive generations of the scholar-official class, yet his official career did not advance greatly. By nature magnanimous and averse to currying favor, he spent his days in the company of worthy scholars and great officers, devoted to their mutual enjoyment, giving no thought to household affairs or property. At the age of sixty-three, in the wuchen year of Tianli, he passed away at his residence.

    His wife was Lady Yi, Great Lady of the Three Han States, granddaughter of Left Vice Premier Yi Qian and daughter of National Academy Libationer Yi Xingian. From a great and virtuous clan, she was a fitting match for a gentleman of standing. They had five sons and three daughters, the youngest of whom became Empress.

    Considering the Ki clan: from the founding of the kingdom they were renowned for martial talents, with their service recorded across generations. The mother of King Ren bore Kings Yi, Ming, and Shen, honored as the Great Empress Gongrui. Minister Ki's grandmother was the granddaughter of Crown Prince Ru, younger brother to the royal mother, and daughter of Judge Jingxun. Thus the Ki and Ren families grew ever greater and more illustrious, supreme among the Eastern Kingdom.

    Attendant-at-Court Kangsheng served as Grand Councilor to Kings Yi, Ming, and Shen. In the final years of King Yi, when the military officer Zheng Zhongfu raised rebellion, assassinating court officials and arbitrarily elevating and deposing rulers, thereafter power-wielding ministers succeeded one another, and officials trembled—yet he alone maintained composure through righteousness, preserving the state through difficult times without losing what had been built. Much credit was his.

    Vice Premier Ki, man of bold integrity, held fast to righteousness when the realm faced tribulation. Though connected by marriage to powerful ministers, he would not stoop to flattery, instead reminding them of the consequences of rebellion and submission. His principled stance prevented schemes from taking root. When he fell ill, his unworthy son Hang attracted many followers, yet Vice Premier Ki alone opposed him, promptly recommending a worthy successor. Upon Hang's succession, the Vice Premier was spurned for his earlier objections and died in bitter disappointment—the times grieved his loss.

    The Three Excellencies was first named Zhang, later changed to avoid the imperial name. Beginning as a general sent to govern Chungju, he championed leniency and gentle administration. Severe penalties were eschewed, and the people dared not deceive him. His governance proved excellent, earning him appointment as Grand General, then promotion to Commander of the Eagle Emblem Army. By state ordinance, military appointments, rewards, punishments, and the advancement of officers were left entirely to the Eagle Emblem Commander. He wielded these powers with ritual propriety rather than personal favor, earning the soldiers' devotion. Thus he rapidly ascended to the rank of Prime Minister. King Chungnyeol, recognizing him as a pillar of the realm and elder statesman, honored him with exceptional courtesy—his sorrow and glory were unmatched.

    Minister Ki's mother was Lady Park, Lady of Yeonheung, daughter of Judge of Law Park Hui and external granddaughter of Minister-at-Court Yi Zangyong and Minister Yi Jingjeon. In the first year of Zhiyuan, when the imperial edict required all princes and regional governors to gather at the capital, the king likewise traveled to the imperial audience. Minister Yi, as Chancellor, accompanied King Chungnyeol before the emperor, receiving unusual favor. His virtue, achievements, and literary talent became known throughout China. The Right Premier, the Duke of Dongping and Zhonghexian, held him in highest regard, offering exceptional courtesy and reserving the seat of honor at his right. The Hanlin Academicians and Royal Scholars all admired his bearing and desired his friendship. All that he accomplished in responding to imperial commands and in advancing the kingdom's interests and removing its harms, the people benefit from even now.

    Minister Ki's family, both maternal and paternal lines, were of great renown. From his great-grandfather, Attendant-at-Court and Chancellor Shoujuan, and his descendants, they served as generals and prime ministers, their merit benefiting the people. Yet they did not enjoy the rewards of their virtue, ending their careers in humble positions. Perhaps Heaven delays their great recompense for generations yet to come.

    His eldest son Shi predeceased him. His second son Zhe, holding the rank of Censor-in-Chief, is now enfeoffed as Duke of Deseong. His third son Yuan, ranking as Censor of Recommendations, is now enfeoffed as Duke of Deyang. His fourth son Zhou holds the rank of Great Minister and Presidential Councilor. His fifth son Lun serves as Right Constant Attendant. His eldest daughter married Zhao Xichong, Commissioner of Investigation. His second daughter married Lian Dunshao, Director of Imperial Secretariat. He had eleven grandsons: the eldest, Tianlin, known familiarly as Wanzhe Puhua, entered service as Director of Maps and now serves as Secretary of the Secretariat. His descendants Tianji, Youji, and Tianlong all hold the rank of Commander. The others remain unranked. He had seven granddaughters, the eldest of whom married Hong Baohuan, Examiner of the Bureau of Merit. The others are yet young.

    Minister Ki's ancestral virtue and merit are recorded in the national history. His deeds shine bright in the eyes and ears of all. This account gathers his major accomplishments as a biographical record, preserved for posterity.

    Respectfully written on the first day of the eighth month of the Zhizhen era.
  footnotes:
